<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:-7.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Item 7.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:-7.333px; text-indent:66px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Overview</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We are an insurance holding company engaged in the insurance and reinsurance business through our wholly owned insurance company, Independence American Insurance Company (&quot;Independence American&quot;), our marketing organizations, including our three medical stop-loss managing general underwriter subsidiaries (&#147;our MGUs&quot;), our two insurance and marketing agencies IPA and HIO, and our claims administration company, ECA. &nbsp;Since November 2002, AMIC has been affiliated with Independence Holding Company (&quot;IHC&quot;), which owned 49.7% of AMIC's stock as of December 31, 2009. &nbsp;In March 2010, upon approval of the AMIC Board of Directors, IHC acquired control of AMIC through the purchase of additional shares of common stock in the open market. &nbsp;IHC's senior management has provided direction to us through service agreements between us and IHC. &nbsp;In 2009, Independence American&#146;s primary source of revenu
e was reinsurance premiums. &nbsp;The majority of these premiums are ceded to Independence American from IHC under long-term reinsurance treaties to cede its gross medical stop-loss premiums written to Independence American. &nbsp;In addition, Independence American assumes fully insured health and short-term statutory disability benefit product in New York State (&quot;DBL&quot;) premiums from IHC, and assumes medical stop-loss premiums from unaffiliated carriers. &nbsp;Independence American began writing group major medical, medical stop-loss, major medical plans for individuals and families, and short-term medical in 2007, and added dental in 2009. &nbsp;Given its A- (Excellent) rating from A.M. Best, Independence American expects to expand the distribution of its medical stop-loss products, and slightly increase the business written on its paper, especially major medical plans for individuals and families.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While management considers a wide range of factors in its strategic planning, the overriding consideration is underwriting profitability. &nbsp;Management's assessment of trends in healthcare and in the medical stop-loss market play a significant role in determining whether to expand Independence American's health insurance premiums. &nbsp;Since Independence American reinsures a portion of all of the business produced by our MGUs, and since these companies are also eligible to earn profit sharing commissions based on the profitability of the business they place, our MGUs also emphasize underwriting profitability. &nbsp;In addition, management focuses on controlling operating costs. &nbsp;By sharing employees with IHC and sharing resources among our subsidiaries, we strive to maximize our earnings.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The following is a summary of key performance information and events:</P>

</TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC; border-bottom:3px double #000000" valign=bottom width=66.2><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt" align=right>965&nbsp;</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol; page-break-before:always" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Net income per share increased to $.31 per share, diluted, or $2.6 million, for the year ended December 31, 2009, compared to $.11 per share, diluted, or $1.0 million for the year ended December 31, 2008. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The book value of the Company&#146;s stockholders&#146; equity increased to $10.46 per share at December 31, 2009 compared to $9.75 per share at December 31, 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2009, 97.5% of the Company's fixed maturities were investment grade.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Consolidated investment yields were 4.6% and 5.3% for the years ended December 31, 2009 and 2008, respectively. &nbsp;The lower yield is due to an increase in more liquid assets which bear lower interest rates.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Premiums earned decreased 12% to $85.5 million for the year ended December 31, 2009 from $97.0 million for the year ended December 31, 2008, primarily due to lower assumed medical stop-loss premiums and lower group major medical premiums written.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company recorded improved loss ratios in both fully insured health and medical stop-loss for the year ended December 31, 2009.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>For the years ended December 31, 2009 and 2008, Independence American wrote $10.9 million and $4.3 million, respectively, of individual health business produced by our marketing organization IPA.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Underwriting experience, as indicated by its GAAP Combined Ratios on our three lines of business for the years ended December 31, 2009 and 2008 are as follows (in thousands):</P>

</TD><TD valign=bottom width=20><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="border-bottom:1px solid #000000" valign=bottom width=73.333><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; padding-left:-7.2px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt" align=right>29.1%</P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=301.733><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Combined Ratio <SUP>(C)</SUP></P>
</TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=top width=15.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC; border-bottom:3px double #000000" valign=bottom width=71.6><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt" align=right>87.7%</P>
</TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=20><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC; border-bottom:3px double #000000" valign=bottom width=73.333><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; padding-left:-7.2px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt" align=right>84.6%</P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="line-height:10pt; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-13.333px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=justify>(A)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Loss ratio represents insurance benefits claims and reserves divided by premiums earned.</P>
<P style="line-height:10pt; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-13.333px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=justify>(B)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Expense ratio represents net commissions (including profit commissions), administrative fees, premium taxes and other underwriting expenses divided by premiums earned.</P>
<P style="line-height:10pt; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-13.333px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=justify>(C)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The combined ratio is equal to the sum of the loss ratio and the expense ratio.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In 2009, our MGUs wrote an aggregate of $54.8 million of annualized gross premium compared to $73.3 million in 2008. &nbsp;This reduction in premiums was due, in part, to planned pricing increases, stricter underwriting guidelines, the continuing generally &quot;soft&quot; market, and liquidation of IndependenceCare.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>CRITICAL ACCOUNTING POLICIES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The accounting and reporting policies of the Company conform to U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (&quot;GAAP&quot;). The preparation of the Consolidated Financial Statements in conformity with GAAP requires the Company's management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the amounts reported in the financial statements and accompanying notes. Actual results could differ from those estimates. A summary of the Company's significant accounting policies and practices is provided in Note 2 of the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8. Management has identified the accounting policies described below as those that, due to the judgments, estimates and assumptions inherent in those policies, are critical to an understanding of the Company's Consolidated Financial Statements and this Management's Discussion and Analysis.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Insurance Reserves</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, where material, including legal and other fees, for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. &nbsp;These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are maintained at levels that are estimated in accordance with GAAP. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s estimate of loss reserves represents management&#146;s best estimate of the Company&#146;s liability at the balance sheet date.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company&#146;s policies are short-duration and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period&#146;s claims or open claims from prior periods, including losses incurred for claims that have not been reported (&#147;IBNR&#148;). Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events. </P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management believes that the Company's methods of estimating the liabilities for insurance reserves provided appropriate levels of reserves at December 31, 2009. Changes in the Company's reserve estimates are recorded through a charge or credit to its earnings.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial"><B>Medical Stop-Loss</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company&#146;s medical stop-loss business is comprised of employer stop-loss and HMO Reinsurance. &nbsp;The two &#147;primary&#148; or &#147;key&#148; assumptions underlying the calculation of loss reserves for medical stop-loss business are (i) projected net loss ratio, and (ii) claim development patterns. &nbsp;The projected net loss ratio is set at expected levels consistent with the underlying assumptions (&#147;Projected Net Loss Ratio&#148;). Claim development </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">21</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>patterns are set quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history (&#147;Claim Development Patterns&#148;). &nbsp;The Company uses the Projected Net Loss Ratio to establish reserves until developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results and it is feasible to set reserves based on Claim Development Patterns. &nbsp;The Company has concluded that a reasonably likely change in the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption could have a material effect on the Company&#146;s financial condition, results of operations, or liquidity (&#147;Material Effect&#148;) but a reasonably likely change in the Claim Development Pattern would not have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Projected Net Loss Ratio</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Generally, during the first twelve months of an underwriting year, reserves for medical stop-loss are first set at the Projected Net Loss Ratio, which is determined using assumptions developed using completed prior experience trended forward. The Projected Net Loss Ratio is the Company&#146;s best estimate of future performance until such time as developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While the Company establishes a best estimate of the Projected Net Loss Ratio, actual experience may deviate from this estimate. &nbsp;This was the case with the 2006, 2007 and 2008 underwriting years that increased (decreased) by 9.7, (1.4), and (2.2) Loss Ratio points, respectively. &nbsp;While the Company believes that larger variations are possible, based on the Company&#146;s experience to date, it is reasonably likely that the actual experience will fall within a range up to five Net Loss Ratio points above or below the expected Projected Net Loss Ratio for 2009 at December 31, 2009. &nbsp;The impact of these reasonably likely changes at December 31, 2009, would be an increase in net reserves (in the case of a higher ratio) or a decrease in net reserves (in the case of a lower ratio) of up to approximately $1.0 million with a corresponding increase or decrease in the pre-tax expense for insurance benefits, claims and reserves 
in the 2009 Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Major factors that affect the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption in reserving for medical stop-loss relate to: (i) frequency and severity of claims; (ii) changes in medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, the impact of new medical technology and changes in medical treatment protocols; and (iii) the adherence by the MGUs that produce and administer this business to applicable underwriting guidelines. &nbsp;Changes in these underlying factors are what determine the reasonably likely changes in the Projected Net Loss Ratio as discussed above.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Claim Development Patterns</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Subsequent to the first twelve months of an underwriting year, the Company&#146;s developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate losses. At this point, claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. &nbsp;Development factors based on historical patterns are applied to paid and reported claims to estimate fully developed claims. Claim Development Patterns are reviewed quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history. The Company must determine whether changes in development represent true indications of emerging experience or are simply due to random claim fluctuations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company also establishes its best estimates of claim development factors to be applied to more developed treaty year experience. &nbsp;While these factors are based on historical Claim Development Patterns, actual claim development may vary from these estimates. &nbsp;The Company does not believe that reasonably likely changes in its actual claim development patterns would have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Predicting ultimate claims and estimating reserves in medical stop-loss is more complex than fully insured medical and disability business due to the &#147;excess of loss&#148; nature of these products with very high deductibles applying to specific claims on any individual claimant and in the aggregate for a given group.&nbsp; The level of these deductibles makes it more difficult to predict the amount and payment pattern of such claims. &nbsp;Fluctuations in results for specific coverage are primarily due to the severity and frequency of individual&nbsp;claims, whereas fluctuations in aggregate coverage are largely attributable to frequency of underlying claims rather than severity. Liabilities for first dollar medical reserves and disability coverages are computed using completion factors and expected loss ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">22</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Due to the short-term nature of medical stop-loss, redundancies or deficiencies will typically emerge during the course of the following year rather than over a number of years. &nbsp;For Employer Stop-Loss, as noted above, the Company maintains its reserves based on underlying assumptions until it determines that an adjustment is appropriate based on emerging experience from all of its MGUs for prior underwriting years. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Fully Insured Health</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Reserves for fully insured medical and dental business are established using historical claim development patterns. &nbsp;Claim development by number of months elapsed from the incurred month is studied each month and development factors are calculated. &nbsp;These claim development factors are then applied to the amount of claims paid to date for each incurred month to estimate fully complete claims. &nbsp;The difference between fully complete claims and the claims paid to date is the estimated reserve. &nbsp;Total reserves are the sum of the reserves for all incurred months.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The primary assumption in the determination of fully insured health reserves is that historical claim development patterns are representative of future claim development patterns. &nbsp;Factors which may affect this assumption include changes in claim payment processing times and procedures, changes in product design, changes in time delay in submission of claims and the incidence of unusually large claims. &nbsp;The reserving analysis includes a review of claim processing statistical measures and large claim early notifications; the potential impact of any changes in these factors are minimal. &nbsp;The time delay in submission of claims tends to be stable over time and not subject to significant volatility. &nbsp;Since our analysis considered a variety of outcomes related to these factors, the Company does not believe that any reasonably likely change in these factors will have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Premium and MGU Fee Income Revenue Recognition </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Direct and assumed premiums from short-duration contracts are recognized as revenue over the period of the contracts in proportion to the amount of insurance protection provided. &nbsp;The Company records MGU fee income as policy premium payments are earned. &nbsp;Our MGUs are compensated in two ways. &nbsp;They earn fee income based on the volume of business produced, and collect profit-sharing commissions if such business exceeds certain profitability benchmarks. &nbsp;Profit-sharing commissions are accounted for beginning in the period in which the Company believes they are reasonably estimable, which is typically at the point that claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Reinsurance</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Amounts recoverable or paid for under reinsurance contracts are included in total assets or total liabilities as due from reinsurers or due to reinsurers. &nbsp;In 2009, Independence American derived most of its business from pro rata quota share reinsurance treaties with Standard Security Life and Madison National Life, which are wholly owned subsidiaries of IHC. &nbsp;These treaties terminate on December 31, 2014, unless terminated sooner by Independence American. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life must cede at least 15% of their medical stop-loss business to Independence American under these treaties. &nbsp;Additionally, Standard Security Life, Madison National Life and Independence American have received regulatory approval to cede up to 30% to Independence American under most of IHC&#146;s medical stop-loss programs. For each of the twelve months ended December 31, 2009 and 2008, Standard Security Life and Madis
on National Life ceded an average of approximately 23% of their medical stop-loss business to Independence American. Independence American reinsures 20% of Standard Security Life&#146;s DBL business. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life also ceded approximately 9% of the majority of their fully insured health business to Independence American. &nbsp;In addition, in 2009, Independence American ceded 40% of its short-term medical and 50% of its major medical for individuals and families business to unaffiliated reinsurers.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Taxes</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In assessing the realizability of deferred tax assets, management considers<B> </B>whether it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized. The ultimate realization of deferred tax </P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">23</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>assets is dependent upon the generation of future taxable income during the period in which those temporary differences become deductible. &nbsp;Management considers the scheduled reversal of deferred tax liabilities, projected future taxable income, and tax planning strategies in making this assessment. &nbsp;Management believes that although sufficient uncertainty exists regarding the future realization of deferred tax assets, the valuation allowance has been adjusted to account for the expected utilization of net operating losses against future taxable income.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has net operating loss carryforwards for federal income tax purposes available to reduce future income subject to income taxes. &nbsp;The net operating loss carryforwards expire between 2019 and 2029.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>U.S. Federal and California tax laws impose substantial restrictions on the utilization of net operating loss and credit carryforwards in the event of an &quot;ownership change&quot; for tax purposes, as defined in Section 382 of the Internal Revenue Code.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investments </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has classified all of its investments as available-for-sale securities. &nbsp;These investments are carried at fair value with unrealized gains and losses reported in accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) in the Consolidated Balance Sheets for available-for-sale securities. &nbsp;Fixed maturities and equity securities available-for-sale totaled $55.1 million and $48.9 million at December 31, 2009 and 2008, respectively. &nbsp;Premiums and discounts on debt securities purchased at other than par value are amortized and accreted, respectively, to interest income in the Consolidated Statements of Operations, using the constant yield method over the period to maturity. &nbsp;Net realized gains and losses on investments are computed using the specific identification method and are reported in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Fair value is determined using quoted market prices when available. In some cases, we use quoted market prices for similar instruments in active markets and/or model-derived valuations where inputs are observable in active markets. When there are limited or inactive trading markets, we use industry-standard pricing methodologies, including discounted cash flow models, whose inputs are based on management assumptions and available current market information. Further, we retain independent pricing vendors to assist in valuing certain instruments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Declines in value of securities available-for-sale that are judged to be other-than-temporary are determined based on the specific identification method. &nbsp;The Company reviews its investment securities regularly and determines whether other-than-temporary impairments have occurred. &nbsp;For fixed maturities, if a decline in fair value is judged by management to be other-than-temporary, and the Company does not intend to sell the security and it is not more likely than not that it will be required to sell the security prior to recovery of the security&#146;s amortized cost, the impairment is bifurcated into (a) the amount of the total impairment related to the credit loss, and (b) the amount of the total impairment related to all other factors. The amount of the other-than-temporary impairment related to the credit loss is recognized by a charge to total other-than-temporary impairment losses in the Consolidated Statements of Operat
ions, establishing a new cost basis for the security. The amount of the other-than-temporary impairment related to all other factors is recognized in other comprehensive income in the Consolidated Balance Sheets. The factors considered by management in its regular review include, but are not limited to: &nbsp;the length of time and extent to which the fair value has been less than cost; the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer; adverse changes in ratings announced by one or more rating agencies; subordinated credit support; whether the issuer of a debt security has remained current on principal and interest payments; current expected cash flows; whether the decline in fair value appears to be issuer specific or, alternatively, a reflection of general market or industry conditions (including, in the case of fixed maturities, the effect of changes in market interest rates); and the Company's intent to sell, or be required to sell, the debt security before the anticipated recovery of its re
maining amortized cost basis. &nbsp;<A NAME="OLE_LINK7"></A><A NAME="OLE_LINK8"></A></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Equity securities may experience other-than-temporary impairment in the future based on the prospects for full recovery in value in a reasonable period of time and the Company&#146;s ability and intent to hold the security to recovery. If a decline in fair value is judged by management to be other-than-temporary or management does not have the intent and ability to hold a security, a loss is recognized by a charge to total other-than-temporary impairment losses in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. For the purpose of other-than-temporary </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">24</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>impairment evaluations, preferred stocks are treated in a manner similar to debt securities. Declines in the creditworthiness of the issuer of debt securities with both debt and equity-like features requires the use of the equity model in analyzing the security for other-than-temporary impairment. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Goodwill and Other Intangibles</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite lives, which consist of licenses, are not amortized but are evaluated for impairment in the aggregate at the end of the fourth quarter of each year, or more frequently if indicators arise. &nbsp;If the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount (including goodwill), further evaluation is required to determine if a write-down of goodwill is required. &nbsp;Any impairment write-down of goodwill would be charged to expense. &nbsp;No impairment charge was required in 2009 or 2008. &nbsp;If the Company experiences a sustained decline in its results of operations and cash flows, or other indicators of impairment exist, the Company may incur a material non-cash charge to earnings relating to impairment of our goodwill, which could have a material adverse effect on our results.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:5.533px" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">25</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>

<TR><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=348.867 colspan=8><P style="line-height:10pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Net income attributable to American Independence Corp.</P>
</TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=top width=81.8 colspan=2><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=top width=66.6 colspan=2><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=top width=82.667 colspan=3><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=top width=18.6><P style="line-height:10pt; margin:0px; padding-left:-6.267px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=right>$</P>
</TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC; border-bottom:3px double #000000" valign=bottom width=54.2><P style="line-height:10pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=right>965&nbsp;</P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Premiums Earned</U></I>. &nbsp;Premiums earned decreased 12%, or $11,469,000 to $85,515,000 for 2009, compared to $96,984,000 for 2008. &nbsp;The Company currently has three lines of business. &nbsp;Premiums relating to medical stop-loss business were $46,378,000 and $54,574,000 for 2009 and 2008, respectively. &nbsp;This is due to a decrease in medical stop-loss premiums assumed by Independence American ($9,443,000), partially offset by an increase in medical stop-loss written by Independence American ($1,247,000). &nbsp;Premiums relating to fully insured health consisting of group major medical, limited medical, short-term medical, dental, vision, and individual health were $35,834,000 and $38,975,000 for 2009 and 2008, respectively. &nbsp;The decrease is primarily </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">26</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>due to a decrease in group major medical premiums written by Independence American ($5,888,000) and a decrease in group major medical premiums assumed from IHC ($862,000), offset by an increase in individual health premiums written by Independence American ($3,306,000). &nbsp;Premiums relating to DBL were $3,303,000 and $3,435,000 for 2009 and 2008, respectively. &nbsp;For 2009, Independence American assumed 10% of IHC&#146;s short-term medical business, approximately 9% of certain of IHC&#146;s group major medical business, 20% of IHC&#146;s DBL business and approximately 23% of IHC&#146;s medical stop-loss business. &nbsp;There were no significant changes to these percentages from the prior year.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>MGU and Agency Income</U></I>. &nbsp;MGU and agency income increased $792,000 to $15,331,000 for 2009, compared to $14,539,000 for 2008. &nbsp;MGU fee income-administration decreased $2,236,000 to $5,586,000 for 2009, compared to $7,822,000 for 2008, as our MGUs have decreased their volume of business as a result of stricter underwriting guidelines. &nbsp;MGU fee income-profit commission decreased $15,000 to $1,021,000 for 2009, compared to $1,036,000 for 2008. &nbsp;Profit commissions for a given year are based primarily on the performance of business written during portions of the three preceding years. &nbsp;Therefore, profit commissions for 2009 are based on business written during portions of 2006, 2007 and 2008. &nbsp;In 2009, income from our Agencies consisted of commission income and other fees of $6,763,000 from IPA, revenue of $1,455,000 from HIO, and $506,000 of claims administration fees from ECA. &nbsp;In 2008, income
 from our Agencies consisted of commission income and other fees of $4,716,000 from IPA and revenue of $965,000 from HIO. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Investment Income</U>.</I> &nbsp;Net investment income decreased $659,000 to $2,924,000 for 2009, compared to $3,583,000 for 2008. &nbsp;The investment yields were 4.6% 2009 and 5.3% for 2008. &nbsp;The lower yield is due to an increase in more liquid assets which bear lower interest rates.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Realized Investment Gains and Other-Than-Temporary Impairment Losses</U>.</I> &nbsp;The Company recorded a net realized investment gain of $275,000 for 2009, compared to a loss of $1,896,000 for 2008. &nbsp;For 2009 and 2008, the Company recorded a realized loss of $0 and $1,006,000, respectively, for other-than-temporary impairments. &nbsp;The loss of $1,006,000 as of December 31, 2008 represents a loss on bonds and preferred stock that the Company determined to be other-than-temporary due to the severity of the decrease in market values and the length of time that these securities were in a loss position. &nbsp;Also, in the fourth quarter of 2008, the Company became aware of certain activities engaged in by the non-affiliate broker-dealer that managed a trading account of the Company. &nbsp;Accordingly, the Company recorded a $2,006,000 loss, net of expected recoveries, in the fourth quarter of 2008 relating to assets invest
ed with this broker-dealer. &nbsp;The Company's decision as to whether to sell securities is based on management&#146;s ongoing evaluation of investment opportunities and economic market conditions, thus creating fluctuations in realized gains or losses from period to period. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Other Income</U>.</I> &nbsp;Other income was $202,000 for 2009 compared to $1,108,000 for 2008. &nbsp;Included in 2009 is income of $205,000 representing a decrease in the fair value of the derivative liability relating to the agreement with Employers Direct Health, Inc. (&#147;EDH&#148;) (see Note 20 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements). &nbsp;Included in 2008 is income of $1,043,000 representing a decrease in the fair value of the derivative liability relating to the agreement with EDH. &nbsp;The unrealized gain for 2009 and 2008 reflects the lower probability of EDH business meeting target benchmarks.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Insurance Benefits, Claims and Reserves.</U></I> &nbsp;Insurance benefits claims and reserves decreased 15%, or $10,456,000 to $59,658,000 for 2009, compared to $70,114,000 for 2008. &nbsp;The decrease of $10,456,000 is primarily comprised of a decrease in assumed medical stop-loss of $6,892,000 and a decrease in direct fully insured of $3,533,000 due to lower premiums written and improved loss ratios in group major medical, slightly offset by higher premiums and higher loss ratios in individual health.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Selling, General and Administrative</U></I>. &nbsp;Selling, general and administrative expenses decreased $1,154,000 to<I> </I>$39,109,000 for 2009, compared to $40,263,000 for 2008. &nbsp;This decrease is primarily due to (i) lower commission expense of $4,022,000 incurred by Independence American primarily resulting from a decrease in premiums assumed in medical stop-loss business and group major medical premiums written, and (ii) lower expenses at IndependenceCare and Marlton of $1,022,000 and $608,000, respectively, primarily due to lower payroll expenses. This was offset by (i) the additional expense at IPA of $3,157,000 which includes commissions and other general expenses of the agency, (ii) $934,000 at ECA, which was formed in the fourth </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">27</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>quarter of 2008, and (iii) an increase in underwriting expenses at Independence American of $540,000 due to costs associated with higher individual health premiums written.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Amortization and Depreciation</U>.</I> &nbsp;Amortization and depreciation expense increased $49,000 to $842,000 for 2009, compared to $793,000 for 2008. &nbsp;The increase in amortization is primarily due to the acquisition of 51% of IPA in 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Income Taxes.</U> &nbsp;</I>The provision for income taxes increased $841,000 to $1,472,000, an effective rate of 36.0%, for 2009, compared to $631,000, an effective rate of 37.8%, for 2008. &nbsp;Net income for 2009 and 2008 includes a non-cash provision for federal income taxes of $1,311,000 and $497,000, respectively. &nbsp;The state tax effective rate decreased to 3.1% for 2009, compared to 8.1% for 2008. &nbsp;As compared to our MGUs, Independence American pays a nominal amount of state income tax; therefore, the Company&#146;s state tax effective rate will decrease relative to an increase in Independence American&#146;s pre-tax income. &nbsp;For as long as AMIC utilizes its NOL carryforwards, it will not pay any income taxes, except for federal alternative minimum taxes and state income taxes.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Gain (loss) on Discontinued Operations.</U></I> &nbsp;Loss on discontinued operations, net of tax was $0 for 2009, compared to $75,000 for 2008. &nbsp;The loss of $75,000 in 2008 was due to the loss of rental income associated with the sublease of a property located in Livermore, California, and a re-estimation of expected expenses related to the lease (see Note 11 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Income attributable to the non-controlling interest</U></I>. &nbsp;The Company recorded net income attributable to the non-controlling interest of $554,000 and $471,000 for 2009 and 2008, respectively. &nbsp;The net income for 2009 relates to the 49% non-controlling interest in IPA and the 49% non-controlling interest in HIO. &nbsp;The net income for 2008 relates to the 20% non-controlling interest in Marlton (through March 31, 2008), the 49% non-controlling interest in IPA, and the 49% non-controlling interest in HIO.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Income attributable to American Independence Corp</U>.</I> &nbsp;The net income attributable to the Company increased 171% to $2,612,000 or $.31 per share, diluted, for 2009, compared to $965,000, or $.11 per share, diluted, for 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Independence American</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American principally derives cash flow from: (i) operations; (ii) the receipt of scheduled principal payments on its portfolio of fixed income securities; and (iii) earnings on investments and other investing activities. &nbsp;Such cash flow is partially used to finance liabilities for insurance policy benefits and reinsurance obligations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Corporate</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Corporate derives cash flow funds principally from: dividends and tax payments from its subsidiaries and investment income from corporate liquidity. &nbsp;The ability of Independence American to pay dividends to its parent company is governed by Delaware insurance laws and regulations; otherwise, there are no regulatory constraints on the ability of any of our subsidiaries to pay dividends to its parent company. &nbsp;For the twelve months ended December 31, 2009, our MGUs and Agencies paid $1,785,000 in dividends to Corporate.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Cash Flows</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As of December 31, 2009, the Company had $60,894,000 of cash, cash equivalents, and investments net of amounts due to/from brokers compared with $57,248,000 as of December 31, 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Net cash provided by operating activities of continuing operations for the year ended December 31, 2009 was $520,000.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">28</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Net cash used by investing activities of continuing operations for the year ended December 31, 2009 was $588,000. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2009, the Company had $5,521,000 of restricted cash at our MGUs. &nbsp;The amount at our MGUs is directly offset by corresponding liabilities for Premium and Claim Funds Payable of $5,521,000. This asset, in part, represents the premium that is remitted by the insureds and is collected by our MGUs on behalf of the insurance carriers they represent. &nbsp;Each month the premium is remitted to the insurance carriers by our MGUs. &nbsp;Until such remittance is made the collected premium is carried as an asset on the balance sheet of each of our MGUs with a corresponding payable to each insurance carrier. &nbsp;In addition to the premium being held at our MGUs, our MGUs are in possession of cash to pay claims. &nbsp;The cash is deposited by each insurance carrier into a bank account that our MGUs can access. &nbsp;The cash is used by our MGUs to pay claims on behalf of the insurance carriers they represent. &nbsp;The availab
ility of cash enables our MGUs to reimburse claims in a timely manner.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2009, the Company had $29,286,000 of insurance reserves that it expects to pay out of current assets and cash flows from future business. &nbsp;If necessary, the Company could utilize the cash received from maturities and repayments of its fixed maturity investments if the timing of claim payments associated with the Company's insurance resources does not coincide with future cash flows.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company believes it has sufficient cash to meet its currently anticipated business requirements over the next twelve months including the funding of discontinued operations, working capital requirements, and capital investments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>BALANCE SHEET</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Total investments, net of amounts due to/from brokers, increased $3,974,000 to $56,821,000 at December 31, 2009 from $52,847,000 at December 31, 2008, primarily due to a decrease in unrealized losses due to a recovery of fixed income securities in the financial markets. &nbsp;The $6,041,000 increase in total stockholders' equity is primarily due to a decrease of $3,231,000 in unrealized losses and net income of $2,612,000 generated during 2009.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company had receivables from reinsurers of $11,011,000 at December 31, 2009. &nbsp;Substantially all of the business ceded to such reinsurers is of short duration. &nbsp;All of such receivables are either due from related parties, highly rated companies or are adequately secured. &nbsp;No allowance for doubtful accounts was deemed necessary at December 31, 2009.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Asset Quality and Investment Impairments</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The nature and quality of insurance company investments must comply with all applicable statutes and regulations, which have been promulgated primarily for the protection of policyholders. Although the Company's gross unrealized losses on available-for-sale securities totaled $1,563,000 at December 31, 2009, approximately 97.5% of the Company&#146;s fixed maturities were investment grade and continue to be rated on average AA. &nbsp;The Company marks all of its available-for-sale securities to fair value through accumulated other comprehensive income or loss. &nbsp;These investments tend to carry less default risk and, therefore, lower interest rates than other types of fixed maturity investments. At December 31, 2009, approximately 2.5% (or $1,249,000) of the carrying value of fixed maturities was invested in non-investment grade fixed maturities (primarily mortgage securities) (investments in such securities have different risks than 
investment grade securities, including greater risk of loss upon default, and thinner trading markets). &nbsp;The increase in non-investment grade securities is primarily due to the downgrades in credit ratings of certain Alt-A mortgage securities. &nbsp;The Company does not have any non-performing fixed maturity investments at December 31, 2009. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2009, the Company had $1,627,000 invested in whole loan CMOs backed by Alt-A mortgages. &nbsp;Of this amount, 53.9% were in CMOs that originated in 2005 or earlier and 46.1% were in CMOs that originated in 2006 or later. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s mortgage security portfolio has no direct exposure to sub-prime mortgages. The unrealized losses for the equity securities was primarily due to wider spreads from preferred </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">29</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>stocks issued by financial institutions following the disruption in credit markets since the time of their acquisition. Some of these financial institutions have exposure to sub-prime mortgages. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Approximately 1.8% of fixed maturities, primarily municipal obligations, in our investment portfolio are insured by financial guaranty insurance companies. &nbsp;The purpose of this insurance is to increase the credit quality of the fixed maturities and their credit ratings. &nbsp;If the obligations of these financial guarantors ceased to be valuable, either through a credit rating downgrade or default, these debt securities would likely receive lower credit ratings by the rating agencies that would reflect the creditworthiness of the various obligors as if the fixed maturities were uninsured. &nbsp;The following table summarizes the credit quality of our fixed maturity portfolio as rated, and as rated if the fixed maturities were uninsured, at December 31, 2009: &nbsp;</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Changes in interest rates, credit spreads, and investment quality ratings may cause the market value of the Company&#146;s investments to fluctuate. &nbsp;The Company does not have the intent to sell nor is it more likely than not that the Company will have to sell debt securities in unrealized loss positions that are not other-than-temporarily impaired before recovery. &nbsp;In the event that the Company&#146;s liquidity needs require the sale of fixed maturity securities in unfavorable interest rate, liquidity or credit spread environments, the Company may realize investment losses.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company reviews its investments regularly and monitors its investments continually for impairments as discussed in Note 2 (J) (vi) of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements. &nbsp;For 2009 and 2008, the Company recorded a realized loss of $0 and $1,006,000, respectively, for other-than-temporary impairments. &nbsp;The following table summarizes the carrying value of securities with fair values less than 80% of their amortized cost at December 31, 2009 by the length of time the fair values of those securities were below 80% of their amortized cost (in thousands):</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The unrealized losses on all remaining available-for-sale securities have been evaluated in accordance with the Company's impairment policy and were determined to be temporary in nature at December 31, 2009. &nbsp;In 2009, the Company experienced a decrease in net unrealized losses of $3,231,000 net of the net cumulative effect adjustment of $99,000 for the adoption of recent investment accounting pronouncements, which increased stockholders' equity by $3,231,000 (reflecting net unrealized losses of $826,000 at December 31, 2009 compared to net unrealized losses of $4,057,000 at December 31, 2008). &nbsp;From time to time, as warranted, the </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">30</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Company may employ investment strategies to mitigate interest rate and other market exposures. &nbsp;Further deterioration in credit quality of the companies backing the securities, further deterioration in the condition of the financial services industry, a continuation of the current imbalances in liquidity that exist in the marketplace, a continuation or worsening of the current economic recession, or additional declines in real estate values may further affect the fair value of these securities and increase the potential that certain unrealized losses be designated as other-than-temporary in future periods and the Company may incur additional write-downs.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Goodwill</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Goodwill represents the excess of the amount we paid to acquire subsidiaries and other businesses over the fair value of their net assets at the date of acquisition. &nbsp;The Company tests goodwill for impairment at least annually and between annual tests if an event or circumstances change that would more likely than not reduce the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying amount. Goodwill is considered impaired when the carrying amount of goodwill exceeds its implied fair value. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company performed its annual test at December 31, 2009 and determined that goodwill was not impaired. &nbsp;<A NAME="OLE_LINK16"></A><A NAME="OLE_LINK17"></A>No impairment charge was required for 2009 as fair value exceeded carrying value by more than 20%. &nbsp;Any impairment write-down of goodwill would be charged to expense. &nbsp;See Note 3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In determining the fair value of each reporting unit, we used an income approach, applying a discounted cash flow method which included a residual value. &nbsp;Based on historical experience, we made assumptions as to: (i) expected future performance and future economic conditions, (ii) projected operating earnings, (iii) projected new and renewal business as well as profit margins on such business, and (iv) a discount rate that incorporated an appropriate risk level for the reporting unit. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management uses a significant amount of judgment in estimating the fair value of the Company&#146;s reporting units. &nbsp;The key assumptions underlying the fair value process are subject to uncertainty and change. &nbsp;The following represent some of the potential risks that could impact these assumptions and the related expected future cash flows: (i) increased competition; (ii) an adverse change in the insurance industry and overall business climate; (iii) changes in state and federal regulations; (iv) rating agency downgrades of our insurance companies; and (v) a sustained and significant decrease in our share price and market capitalization. &nbsp;As a result of the global economic crisis that began in 2008, we experienced a significant decline in our stock price. Due to this significant decline, our market capitalization as of December 31, 2009 and 2008 was significantly below the sum of our reporting units&#146; fair values. If
 we experience a sustained decline in our results of operations and cash flows, or other indicators of impairment exist, we may incur a material non-cash charge to earnings relating to impairment of our goodwill, which could have a material adverse effect on our results.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>CAPITAL RESOURCES</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As Independence American&#146;s total adjusted capital was significantly in excess of the authorized control level risk-based capital, the Company remains well positioned to increase or diversify its current activities. It is anticipated that future acquisitions or other expansion of operations will be funded internally from existing capital and surplus and parent company liquidity. In the event additional funds are required, it is expected that they would be borrowed or raised in the public or private capital markets to the extent determined to be necessary or desirable.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>OUTLOOK</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Independence American</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American, which is domiciled in Delaware, is licensed to write property and/or casualty insurance in 49 states and the District of Columbia, and has an A- (Excellent) rating from A.M. Best Company, Inc. (&quot;A.M. Best&quot;). An A.M. Best rating is assigned after an extensive quantitative and qualitative evaluation of a company's financial condition and operating performance, and is also based upon factors relevant to </P>

<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">31</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>policyholders, agents, and intermediaries, and is not directed towards protection of investors. A.M. Best ratings are not recommendations to buy, sell or hold securities of the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Since its acquisition by AMIC in 2002, Independence American&#146;s primary source of revenue has been reinsurance premiums. &nbsp;We are beginning to become less dependent on reinsurance premiums as we increased the amount of business written by Independence American. &nbsp;During 2009, Independence American wrote group major medical, medical stop-loss, major medical plans for individuals and families, a small amount of short-term medical and dental. Given its A- (Excellent) rating from A.M. Best, Independence American expects to expand the distribution of its products. &nbsp;In late 2008, Independence American appointed a second MGU, which increased the amount of medical stop-loss business written by Independence American in 2009. &nbsp;We continue to seek additional production sources. &nbsp;With respect to major medical plans for individuals and families, the acquisition of a controlling interest in IPA in 2008, meaningfully increas
ed the amount of this line of business written by Independence American in 2009.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>IHC Treaties</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>With respect to the IHC Treaties, the Company&#146;s operating results are affected by the following factors: (i) the percentage of business ceded to Independence American pursuant to the IHC Treaties; (ii) the amount of gross premium written by Standard Security Life or Madison National Life that is ceded to the IHC Treaties; and (iii) the amount of gross premium produced by the MGUs and other distribution sources written by carriers other than Standard Security Life or Madison National Life that is ceded to Independence American. &nbsp;The profitability of the business ceded will also impact our operating results. &nbsp;Independence American assumes medical stop-loss, fully insured health and DBL premiums from IHC under the IHC Treaties.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Percentage of Business Ceded</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In 2010 and beyond, the percentage of medical stop-loss ceded to Independence American will depend on how much IHC determines it has available to reinsure and Independence American&#146;s desire to reinsure IHC&#146;s business. &nbsp;Since the percentage being ceded is now well in excess of the contractual minimum, there is no guarantee that IHC will continue to increase the percentage of business ceded to Independence American or, in fact, cede in excess of 15%. &nbsp;However, our MGUs are significant producers of medical stop-loss business for IHC.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American reinsures 20% of Standard Security Life&#146;s DBL product. &nbsp;Standard Security Life is not contractually obligated to continue to cede this business to Independence American after termination of the current treaty year. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life ceded approximately 9% of their fully insured health business to Independence American. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life are not contractually obligated to continue to cede this business to Independence American after termination of the current treaty years. &nbsp;The Company does not expect the percentage ceded to it from IHC will change significantly in the next twelve months.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>If Independence American, Standard Security Life, and Madison National Life had agreed to increase the average percentage ceded to Independence American by 1% (from approximately 23% ceded for the twelve months ended December 31, 2009) and Standard Security Life&#146;s and Madison National Life&#146;s gross written premium had remained unchanged, Independence American&#146;s premium would have increased by approximately $1.3 million, which is approximately 1.5% of total net premiums earned for the year ended December 31, 2009. &nbsp;That increase in premium, however, would not have flowed directly to pre-tax operating income because of corresponding changes in insurance benefits, claims and reserves and other expenses attributable to the increase in premiums.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Amount of Premiums Written</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The gross medical stop-loss premiums written by IHC decreased in 2009 by approximately 26% and such premiums produced by our MGUs decreased by approximately 19% in 2009 as a result of writing and/or renewing fewer policies due to competitors' willingness to write business at profit margins lower than those acceptable to the Company, partially offset by increased rates on the policies retained. &nbsp;This resulted in a </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">32</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>decrease in the gross amount of premium available to be ceded to Independence American in 2009, which decrease could extend into 2010. &nbsp;Our MGUs do not anticipate materially increasing their production of medical stop-loss business in 2010. &nbsp;IHC has reported that it expects its fully insured premiums to increase slightly and its DBL premiums to decrease slightly in 2010. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Profitability</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The medical stop-loss market is generally cyclical in nature. When a product experiences several consecutive years of underwriting profitability, it is not unusual for there to be more competitors entering that line which can increase pressure on pricing and create a &#147;softer&#148; market. The medical stop-loss market began to &#147;soften&#148; in 2003 and less favorable conditions continued through 2009. &nbsp;As a result of these market conditions, the rate that the carriers that cede business to the Company were able to charge for medical stop-loss increased at a lesser rate in recent years although increases in medical trend have also been held in check to a greater extent and deductibles and attachment points have increased. This reduces the risk taker&#146;s overall risk exposure.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>Marketing Agreements</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In February 2006, Independence American entered into an agreement with a marketing organization with a block of fully insured health business primarily sold to small employer groups, and medical stop-loss, to begin writing for Independence American. &nbsp;The organization that produces this business began writing employer medical stop-loss through Independence American in 2006, and moved the majority of its existing block of fully insured and stop-loss health insurance to Independence American during 2007. &nbsp;Independence American will be the exclusive issuing carrier for business underwritten by this organization through December 31, 2011. &nbsp;Subject to certain conditions, the agreement will automatically extend until December 31, 2016, and this organization could be entitled to additional cash consideration (see Note 20 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In addition, in 2007 IPA, a national career agent marketing organization, began marketing health plans to individuals and families utilizing Independence American as the carrier. &nbsp;Independence American retains 50% of the risk on this business. &nbsp;Gross premiums of $10,906,000 and $4,295,000 were written under this program in 2009 and 2008, respectively. &nbsp;The program is administered by Insurers Administrative Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of IHC. &nbsp;AMIC purchased a 51% interest in IPA in April 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:-7.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Item 7A.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:-7.333px; text-indent:66px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>&nbsp;<I>Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Not applicable</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>

<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">33</P>

<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">34</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center>&nbsp;<B><U>Report of Management on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The management of American Independence Corp. (&quot;AMIC&quot;) is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting. AMIC's internal control system was designed to provide reasonable assurance to the Company's management and Board of Directors regarding reliability of financial reporting and the preparation and fair presentation of published financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All internal control systems, no matter how well designed, have inherent limitations. Therefore, even those systems determined to be effective can provide only reasonable assurance with respect to financial statement preparation and presentation. &nbsp;Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management assessed the effectiveness of AMIC's internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2009. In making this assessment, management used the criteria set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) in <I>Internal Control &#150;Integrated Framework</I>. Based on our assessment we concluded that, as of December 31, 2009, AMIC's internal control over financial reporting is effective.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">35</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:14.467px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>&nbsp;Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.:</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries (the &#147;Company&#148;) as of December 31, 2009 and 2008, and the related consolidated statements of operations, changes in stockholders&#146; equity and cash flows for the years then ended. In connection with our audits of the consolidated financial statements, we have also audited the financial statement schedules I to III and V. &nbsp;These consolidated financial statements and schedules are the responsibility of the Company&#146;s management. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these consolidated financial statements and schedules based on our audits.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We conducted our audits in accordance with the auditing standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. The Company is not required to have, nor were we engaged to perform, an audit of its internal control over financial reporting. &nbsp;Our audit included consideration of internal control over financial reporting as a basis for designing audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting. Accordingly, we express no such opinion. An audit also includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements, assessing the accounting p
rinciples used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries as of December 31, 2009 and 2008, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for the years then ended in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;Also in our opinion, the related financial statement schedules, when considered in relation to the basic consolidated financial statements taken as a whole, present fairly, in all material respects, the information set forth therein.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As discussed in Note 2 and Note 6, effective April 1, 2009, the Company changed its method of evaluating other-than-temporary impairments of fixed maturity securities due to the adoption of new accounting requirements issued by the Financial Accounting Standards Board.</P>

<TR><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=441.133 colspan=3><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; padding-left:-5.2px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Decrease in cash and cash equivalents</P>
</TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=26.667><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=71><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt" align=right>(328)</P>

</TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=26.667><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=71><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=27.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="background-color:#CCFFCC" valign=bottom width=68.333><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt" align=right>&nbsp;</P>
